summary: Dallas Cowboys quarterback Dak Prescott will miss the remainder of the season after undergoing surgery on his injured hamstring. However, the Cowboys will now be without their starting quarterback for the rest of the season. This news comes as a major blow to the Cowboys, who are currently 4-5 and in the midst of a playoff race. Prescott has been a key part of the Cowboys' success in recent years, and his absence will be felt. The team will now turn to backup quarterback Cooper Rush to lead the offense. Rush has started two games for the Cowboys this season, going 1-1. He will need to step up and play well in order for the Cowboys to remain in contention.

name: Brendan Carr
summary: President Trump has selected Brendan Carr, an FCC commissioner who played a key role in drafting a 2025 roadmap for the agency, to lead the Federal Communications Commission. Carr's appointment has been met with mixed reactions; some see him as a qualified and experienced choice, while others raise concerns about his past comments and positions on issues such as net neutrality and media ownership rules. Carr is known as a critic of Big Tech companies and has called for stricter regulation of social media platforms. He has also expressed support for rolling back net neutrality regulations, which would allow internet service providers to control the flow of online traffic and potentially slow down or block access to certain websites.

name: Daikin
summary: The Houston Astros have announced that Minute Maid Park will be renamed Daikin Park, effective January 1, 2024. This change comes as part of a new 15-year naming rights deal with Daikin Industries, a Japanese air conditioning manufacturer. Daikin is a global leader in the HVAC industry and has a strong presence in the United States. This deal marks a significant investment by Daikin in the Houston community and will provide the Astros with a major source of revenue. The new name, Daikin Park, will be used for all official signage, marketing materials, and broadcasts.
